         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility"> ¶ I shall enjoy greater facilities in deciphering some of the Diagnoses in plant Preiss ¶  by the acquisition of the herbarium of the late Dr Steetz, which I have purchased. ¶  I hope thus to turn so...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">63.07.00a</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To George Bentham</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RBG Kew, Kew correspondence, Australia, Mueller, 1858-70, f. 9.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">The references to the work on <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Flora australiensis</seg> indicate that the addressee was Bentham. The manuscript was written by M. The fragment may belong with another letter to Bentham.</p>
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 9pt; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0.1598in; "
                     xml:lang="en">MS annotation 'vol. ii’, i.e. Bentham (1863-78), vol. 2. MS dated to July 1863 as the earliest likely date it could have been written, given M's reference to the printed sheets dealing with<seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Acacia">Acacia</name>
                     </seg>; see n. 9 below. </p>
               </note>
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I shall enjoy greater facilities in deciphering some of the Diagnoses in plant Preiss<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Lehmann (1844-7).</p>
               </note> by the acquisition of the herbarium of the late Dr Steetz, which I have purchased.<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">M purchased the herbarium of Joachim Steetz for £80 in 1863 (see Short &amp; Sinkora (1988)), and received it in early December 1863 (M to G. Bentham, 12 December 1863).</p>
               </note> I hope thus to turn some of the West Australian plants of my own collection to good account by critical comparison. What is <name key="Psoralia%20Drummondi">Psoralia Drummondi</name>
               <note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Psoralea drummondii</seg>?</p>
               </note> Meisn? I see nothing but position of leaves to separate <name key="Pultenaea%20epacridea">Pultenaea epacridea</name> from P. ternata and they may therefore be united as P. Cunninghami<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Pultenaea cunninghamii</seg>? </p>
               </note> rendering thus the transit to <name key="Spadostylis">Spadostylis</name> absolutely complete. <name key="Pultenaea%20euchila">Pultenaea euchila</name> is certainly a Pultenaea</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>We are of course anxious to get out the 30 copies of the flora for our Government. Will you be so kind to see that Lovell Reeves does not delay the sending and that I get at least [2] copies bound by the mail.<note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">The first volume of <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Flora australiensis</seg> was published on 30 May 1863 and M received 30 copies on 8 December 1863 (M to J. McCulloch, 8 December 1863).</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>You will receive in the next box all the carpologic specimens of my <name key="Leguminosae">Leguminosae</name> (Australeae) You have given Mr Horatio Tozer's name (after whom the <name key="Myrtus%20Tozeri">Myrtus Tozeri</name>) as Thozets who is A Thozet at Rockhampton.<note xml:id="ftn7" type="footnote" n="7">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Presumably in the sheets of vol. 2 of <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Flora australiensis </seg>
                     <seg style="">sent successively to M after Bentham corrected proofs and the sheets were printed for the volume. The name was not corrected; </seg>see Bentham (1863-78), vol. 2, pp. 424-5.</p>
               </note> The former gentleman in his endeavour to obtain [fruit] specimens of the magnificent <name key="Pithecolobium%20Tozerii">Pithecolobium Tozerii</name> met with so serious accident through the fall of his horse that he was laid up for a very long time and has never fully recovered from it. So be so good to retain his name for that plant.<note xml:id="ftn8" type="footnote" n="8">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">B65.04.01, p. 10.</p>
               </note> The unfortunate Gentleman resides on the Hastings River. I forgot to quote in my review of Victor. <name key="Acacia">Acacia</name>e,<note xml:id="ftn9" type="footnote" n="9">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Presumably for his <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Flora of Victoria</seg>, of which he had sent to Bentham (see M to G. Bentham, 23 July 1863) the first five printed sheets (40 pages) of the second volume, including <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Acacia">Acacia</name>
                     </seg>. (B63.13.06). No further sheets were printed, and the volume was never published.</p>
               </note> that Link in his Handbuch zür Erkennung dur Gewächsecalls the phyllodeous species <name key="Phyllodoces">Phyllodoces</name>!<note xml:id="ftn10" type="footnote" n="10">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Link (1829-33) vol. 2, p. 132.</p>
               </note> As they are diagnostified as such, these synonyms must unavoidably for completeness sake be quoted.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I should have perhaps not commenced to work upon <name key="Chorozema">Chorozema</name>
               <note xml:id="ftn11" type="footnote" n="11">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">M described a number of <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Chorozema">Chorozema</name>
                     </seg> spp. in B63.09.01.</p>
               </note> had I not to finish off the sheets on <name key="Acacia">Acacia</name>e, to release typus. I shall discontinue now publishing that work until I have back the material from you &amp; implore you to use every care that it safely is shipped and always carefully packed and sealed up. The expenses therewith connected can not be great and I feel sure you will spare none to secure safety and good conservation for this important series of plants without which I cannot proceed with my careful &amp; critical review of Victor. plants. The supplements to vol. 1 must fill some sheets, which will make up for what you have devoted in vol 1 for introductions &amp;c &amp;c.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <seg style="">I see <name key="Chorizema%20platylobioides">Chorizema platylobioides</name> = <name key="Mirbelia%20grandiflora">Mirbelia grandiflora</name>.</seg>
            </p>
